items.text: **Laurel** is a [[LINK|lang_en|City|city]] in [[LINK|lang_en|Maryland|Maryland]], located almost midway between [[LINK|lang_en|Washington,_D.C.|Washington, D.C.]], and [[LINK|lang_en|Baltimore|Baltimore]] on the banks of the [[LINK|lang_en|Patuxent_River|Patuxent River]]. While the city limits are entirely in northern [[LINK|lang_en|Prince_George%27s_County,_Maryland|Prince George's County]], outlying developments extend into  [[LINK|lang_en|Anne_Arundel_County|Anne Arundel County]] and [[LINK|lang_en|Howard_County,_MD|Howard County]].[[CITE|6|https://geonames.usgs.gov/apex/f?p=gnispq:3:::NO::P3_FID:597667]] Founded as a [[LINK|lang_en|Mill_town|mill town]] in the early 19th century, the arrival of the [[LINK|lang_en|Baltimore_%26_Ohio_Railroad|Baltimore & Ohio Railroad]] in 1835 expanded local industry and later enabled the city to become an early [[LINK|lang_en|Commuter_town|commuter town]] for Washington and Baltimore workers. Largely residential today, the city maintains a [[LINK|lang_en|Historic_district|historic district]] centered on its [[LINK|lang_en|Main_Street|Main Street]], highlighting its industrial past.

The [[LINK|lang_en|U.S._Department_of_Defense|Department of Defense]] is a prominent presence in the Laurel area today, with the [[LINK|lang_en|Fort_George_G._Meade|Fort Meade]] [[LINK|lang_en|United_States_Army|Army]] base, the [[LINK|lang_en|National_Security_Agency|National Security Agency]], and Johns Hopkins University's [[LINK|lang_en|Applied_Physics_Laboratory|Applied Physics Laboratory]] all located nearby. [[LINK|lang_en|Laurel_Park_(race_track)|Laurel Park]], a [[LINK|lang_en|Thoroughbred_racing|thoroughbred horse racetrack]], is located just outside city limits.
History
Natural history

Many [[LINK|lang_en|Dinosaur|dinosaur]] fossils from the [[LINK|lang_en|Cretaceous|Cretaceous]] Era are preserved in a 7.5-acre (3.0Â ha) [[LINK|lang_en|Dinosaur_Park_(Prince_George%27s_County,_Maryland)|park in Laurel]].[[CITE|7|https://web.archive.org/web/20091125115904/http://www.pgparks.com/About-Parks-and-Recreation/HomePage_Read_More/Dinosaur_Park_Officially_Dedicated_and_Opened_To_the_Public.htm]] The site, which among other finds has yielded fossilized teeth from [[LINK|lang_en|Astrodon|Astrodon]] and [[LINK|lang_en|Priconodon|Priconodon]] species, has been called the most prolific in the eastern United States.[[CITE|8|http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2009-10-25/news/0910240109_1_maryland-state-dinosaur-amateur-paleontologist-cretaceous]] From the Late Glacial age in 10,700 B.C. to 8,500 B.C., Laurel's climate warmed and changed from a spruce forest to a hardwood forest. In the [[LINK|lang_en|Archaic_period_in_North_America|Late Archaic]] period from 4,000 to 1,000 B.C., Laurel would have been covered primarily with an oak and hickory forest.[[CITE|9|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=Conrad%20Jay%20Bladey%2C%20Helen%20Curtis.%20*Human%20Adaptation]]
Pre-20th century

Laurel was formed from land on the [[LINK|lang_en|Atlantic_Seaboard_fall_line|fall line]] of the [[LINK|lang_en|Patuxent_River|Patuxent River]] patented by the [[LINK|lang_en|Richard_Snowden_(ironmaster)|Snowden family]] in 1658 as part of the 12,250-acre [[LINK|lang_en|Birmingham_Manor_(Maryland)|New Birmingham plantation]], which included the later [[LINK|lang_en|Montpelier_Mansion_(Laurel,_Maryland)|Montpelier]].[[CITE|10|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=Conrad%20Jay%20Bladey%2C%20Helen%20Curtis.%20*Human%20Adaptation]] The Washington Turnpike Road Company built Route 1 between 1796 and 1812, creating a major North-South land route. Milstead's Hotel halfway house was built in town to serve four stage lines a day in 1816.[[CITE|11|https://web.archive.org/web/20120201145617/https://www.cityoflaurel.org/sites/default/files/u24/2009%20Master%20Plan.pdf]][[CITE|12|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=Barbara%20Feaga.%20*Howard's%20Roads%20to%20the%20Past*.%20p.%C2%A065]] Nicholas Snowden built a [[LINK|lang_en|Grist_mill|grist mill]] on the site circa 1811 which grew to a small [[LINK|lang_en|Cotton_mill|cotton mill]] by the 1820s.[[CITE|13|https://web.archive.org/web/20070920010327/http://www.stmarys.laurel.md.us/index.php?p=history]]
In 1828, a detailed survey was conducted to build a canal from Baltimore to Georgetown to connect to the proposed [[LINK|lang_en|Chesapeake_and_Ohio_Canal|C&O canal]]. The route from [[LINK|lang_en|Elkridge_Landing|Elkridge Landing]] to Bladensburg would have built a waterway roughly aligning with modern [[LINK|lang_en|U.S._Route_1_in_Maryland|U.S. Route 1]] and [[LINK|lang_en|Kenilworth_Avenue|Kenilworth Avenue]], with special consideration not to harm the water power for [[LINK|lang_en|Savage_Mill|Savage Mill]]. The project did not go forward; the preference was to build a railroad, the [[LINK|lang_en|Baltimore_and_Ohio_Railroad|B&O]].[[CITE|14|http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015091128903;view=1up;seq=11]] Nicholas Snowden died in 1831, and the mill properties transferred to Louisa Snowden and her husband Horace Capon in 1834. In 1835, coinciding with the opening of the [[LINK|lang_en|Capital_Subdivision|Capital Subdivision]]
rail line from Baltimore to Washington, the Patuxent Manufacturing Company was chartered by Horace Capon, Edward Snowden, Theodore Jenkins, W.C. Shaw, A.E. Hall, and O.C. Tiffany and the mill expanded greatly with the addition of the Avondale Mill building in 1844.[[CITE|15|https://web.archive.org/web/20070929184835/http://www.anacostiatrails.org/site/media/ATHAnewsletterVol3No2.pdf]] Mill president [[LINK|lang_en|Horace_Capron|Horace Capron]] with his partners built housing for close to 300 workers, and a bigger cotton mill.[[CITE|16|http://www.heritage.umd.edu/CHRSWeb/AssociatedProjects/chidesterreport/Chapter%20VI.htm#_ftnref218]] [[LINK|lang_en|Cotton_duck|Cotton duck]] from the mill was shipped down what would become Laurel's Main Street, then by rail to Baltimore.[[CITE|17|https://web.archive.org/web/20070625181443/http://www.laurelhistory.org/histsoc.html]] A substantial [[LINK|lang_en|Dam|dam]] was built in 1850.[[CITE|18|https://web.archive.org/web/20070128185638/http://www.mdhc.org/resources/ATHAReport_part4of6.pdf]] As a mill town, Laurel was somewhat unusual in Prince George's County and was surrounded by agricultural endeavors.[[CITE|16|http://www.heritage.umd.edu/CHRSWeb/AssociatedProjects/chidesterreport/Chapter%20VI.htm#_ftnref218]]

The community was originally known as "Laurel Factory" when Edward Snowden became the first postmaster in 1837 and was a true company town, with a school and shops, and many of the mill workers' homes owned until the 1860s by the company.[[CITE|16|http://www.heritage.umd.edu/CHRSWeb/AssociatedProjects/chidesterreport/Chapter%20VI.htm#_ftnref218]]  During the 1840s, three historic churches in the communityâthe [[LINK|lang_en|First_United_Methodist_Church_(Laurel,_Maryland)|Methodist]] Est. 1842,[[CITE|19|https://web.archive.org/web/20070716074301/http://fumcl.org/about/history.php]] St. Mary of the Mills (Roman Catholic) Est. 1845,[[CITE|13|https://web.archive.org/web/20070920010327/http://www.stmarys.laurel.md.us/index.php?p=history]] and St. Philip's (Episcopal) Est. 1839 [[CITE|20|https://web.archive.org/web/20061112091652/http://www.stphilipslaurel.org/Profile.pdf]]âestablished what are still vigorous congregations.  During the [[LINK|lang_en|American_Civil_War|Civil War]], Laurel Factory, like much of Maryland, was a divided community, but with many Southern sympathizers.  Union soldiers patrolled the railroad, and for a time there was also a Union hospital.  During the latter half of the 19th century, while it still operated its factories, manufacturing played a less important role in the community.  Laurel evolved into an early suburban town.  Many of its residents commuted by rail to jobs in Washington or Baltimore. The town was incorporated in 1870 and reincorporated in 1890 to coincide with a new [[LINK|lang_en|Electric_power|electric power]] [[LINK|lang_en|Power_plant|plant]] and [[LINK|lang_en|Pavement_(material)|paved]] streets and boarded sidewalks. By this time, the town had grown to a population of 2,080, and the city banned livestock from the streets.[[CITE|21|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=%22Mayor%20Cull's%20Trials%22.%20*The%20Sunday%20Herald*.%20Septem]]

In 1870, the Patuxent Bank of Laurel was founded on the corner of Main Street and Washington Avenue.[[CITE|22|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=Howard%20County%20Historical%20Society.%20*Images%20of%20Ameri]] In 1874 a delegation was sent to Annapolis to introduce legislation to make Laurel its own county of 10,000 residents with land from Prince George's, Howard, and Anne Arundel counties.[[CITE|23|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=%22New%20County%20Movement%20in%20Maryland%22.%20*The%20Evening%20St]] In 1879 Laurel Academy of Music was built along Route 1. The building was converted to a movie theatre in 1915, with a parking garage on the lower floor of the wood structure; it burned in 1917, and Academy Ford built on the same site in the late 20th century.[[CITE|24|/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number]] In 1888 inventor David J. Weems tested an unmanned electric train on a two-mile banked circular track near Laurel Station. The three-ton vehicle reached speeds of up to 120Â mph for twenty minutes.[[CITE|25|https://web.archive.org/web/20140125021930/http://www.catskillarchive.com/rrextra/odweems.Html]][[CITE|26|/wiki/Federal_Writers%27_Project]]

In 1890, [[LINK|lang_en|Citizens_National_Bank_(Laurel,_Maryland)|Citizens National Bank]] opened its doors on Main Street, as Prince George's County's first nationally chartered bank. [[LINK|lang_en|Charles_H._Stanley|Charles H. Stanley]] was the bank's first president, and it remained independently managed and with the same name until acquired by [[LINK|lang_en|PNC_Financial_Services|PNC Financial Services]] in 2007.[[CITE|27|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=*The%20National%20Cyclop%C3%A6dia%20of%20American%20Biography%3A%20Be]][[CITE|28|http://www.gazette.net/stories/090607/busiplo154436_32356.shtml]][[CITE|29|https://web.archive.org/web/20080523082928/http://news.mywebpal.com/news_tool_v2.cfm?pnpid=810&show=archivedetails&ArchiveID=1293808&om=1]] [[LINK|lang_en|Branch_(banking)|Branch]] services are still provided from the original building.

At the turn of the century, Louis Barret operated a hotel called the "Half Way House", later called the Milstead Hotel, which served as a stop for the four stage lines operating between Baltimore and Washington. In 1898, a stable fire spread to the 100-year-old hotel and burned adjacent buildings along Main Street. With only bucket brigades, Mayor Phelps telegraphed Baltimore to send a special train with fireman, horses, and engine number 10. One fireman was crushed by the rolling fire engine, and returned in a casket saved from the burning mortuary. The resulting losses inspired efforts to bring water and fire apparatus to the town.[[CITE|30|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=%22Laurel%20Swept%20By%20Fire%2C%20Destructive%20Conflagration%20i]][[CITE|31|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=%22Laurel%20to%20Have%20Water%20and%20Lights%22.%20*The%20Washington]] The town was struck again by the great Laurel fire of December 14, 1899, when a twelve-building fire destroyed the Laurel Presbyterian Church (known then as Presbyterian Church at Laurel).[[CITE|32|/wiki/Help:CS1_errors#citation_missing_title]]

Proposed in 1897, Laurel's seven-term mayor [[LINK|lang_en|Edward_Phelps_(mayor)|Edward Phelps]] succeeded in constructing the first [[LINK|lang_en|High_school_(North_America)|high school]] in [[LINK|lang_en|Prince_George%27s_County|Prince George's County]] in 1899, despite several financial obstacles, by personally assuming the financial risks in doing so. The original building built for $5,000, now known as the [[LINK|lang_en|Laurel_High_School_(Laurel,_Maryland)|Phelps Community Center]], still stands at the northeast corner of Montgomery and Eighth Streets.[[CITE|33|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=%22Laurel%20Asks%20for%20a%20High%20School%22.%20*The%20Baltimore%20Su]] It was listed on the [[LINK|lang_en|National_Register_of_Historic_Places|National Register of Historic Places]] in 1979.[[CITE|34|http://nrhp.focus.nps.gov/natreg/docs/All_Data.html]]
20th century

In 1902, the City and Suburban Railway with the City and Suburban and Washington, Berwyn, and Laurel railway started single line electric trolley service.[[CITE|35|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=%22LAUREL%20LINE%20OPENED.%3A%20Guests%20of%20Road%20Make%20the%20Firs]]

The [[LINK|lang_en|Laurel_Sanitarium|Laurel Sanitarium]] was built in 1905 on a 163-acre (0.66Â km [[CITE||undefined]] ) farm that comprised what is now Laurel Lakes. The facility's purpose was to care for people with nervous diseases, alcohol, and drug addiction. Five buildings that were joined to a central administration building included 8-, 14-, 30-, and 36-room facilities for men and women.[[CITE|36|https://books.google.com/?id=dC4wAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA579]]

[[LINK|lang_en|Laurel_Park_Racecourse|Laurel Park Racecourse]], a [[LINK|lang_en|Thoroughbred_racing|thoroughbred]] [[LINK|lang_en|Racetrack|racetrack]], opened in 1911 and remains in operation. In the book, *[[LINK|lang_en|Seabiscuit:_An_American_Legend|Seabiscuit: An American Legend]]*, Laurel is mentioned several times as an important horse racing venue. Laurel also hosted a horse trotter ([[LINK|lang_en|Harness_racing|harness racing]]) track named [[LINK|lang_en|Freestate_Raceway|Freestate Raceway]] from 1948 to 1990;[[CITE|37|https://web.archive.org/web/20110516195205/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-1210279.html]][[CITE|38|https://web.archive.org/web/20110516195211/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-1108090.html]] it was located in Howard County on the west side of US Route 1, south of [[LINK|lang_en|Savage,_Maryland|Savage]] in an area that now includes a [[LINK|lang_en|CarMax|CarMax]] dealership, [[LINK|lang_en|Weis_Markets|Weis]] supermarket, and a [[LINK|lang_en|Strip_mall|strip mall]].

In March 1912, the city agreed to take out $35,000 in loans to build its first sewer system with twelve miles of line that terminated by dumping into the [[LINK|lang_en|Patuxent_River|Patuxent River]].[[CITE|39|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=%22Sewerage%20for%20Laurel%22.%20*The%20Baltimore%20Sun*.%20March%20]]

In February 1913, Laurel was a stopping point in the [[LINK|lang_en|Suffrage_hike|Suffrage hike]] led by [[LINK|lang_en|Rosalie_Gardiner_Jones|Rosalie Gardiner Jones]]. She was joined by a Laurel-based colored women's suffrage group and sent a parcel with a flag and message ahead to President-elect [[LINK|lang_en|Woodrow_Wilson|Wilson]].[[CITE|40|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=%22Suffrage%20Hikers%20send%20Wilson%20a%20Flag%22.%20*New%20York%20Ti]]

[[LINK|lang_en|Board_track_racing|Board track racing]] came to Laurel in 1925 when a 1.125-mile (1.811Â km) wood oval track was built by Jack Prince and featured 48-degree banked turns. The Washington-Baltimore automobile speedway was short-lived, with featured races of 16 drivers at a time.[[CITE|41|https://www.loc.gov/pictures/item/npc2008007949]] Despite crowds of up to 30,000, receipts did not cover the $400,000 cost of building the track on the 364-acre Avondale property which fell into receivership in 1926.[[CITE|42|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=%22LAUREL%20SPEEDWAY%20IN%20RECEIVERS'%20HANDS%3A%20Action%20Taken]]
[[LINK|lang_en|Natural_gas|Natural gas]] service was extended to the community in 1929.[[CITE|43|https://www.scribd.com/doc/7625971/City-of-Laurel-Master-Plan-Comprehensive-Amendment]]

In 1931, "Angy Gerrin" built a 7,000-seat amphitheater next to the [[LINK|lang_en|Duvall_Farm|Duvall Farm]] between [[LINK|lang_en|Laurel_Park_(race_track)|Laurel Park]] and Route One for an outdoor boxing venue. His company, Mid City Boxing Club Inc, held several events with low turnouts and receipts confiscated by local police. It was sold the same year to C.E. Cornell, who called it "Twin Cities Arena" or "Mid City Arena".[[CITE|44|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=%22DOUBLE%20BOXING%20CARD%20TONIGHT%3A%20Brown-Firpo%20Bout%20Feat]] The arena was active through 1932 with the entire delegation of the [[LINK|lang_en|World_Boxing_Association|National Boxing Association]] attending a fight with [[LINK|lang_en|Albert_Ritchie|Governor Ritchie]] in attendance.[[CITE|45|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=Jesse%20A.%20Linthicum%20(19%20September%201932).%20%22N.%20B.%20A.%2C]] After watching the match and calling a fight to be halted in five rounds, the delegation announced efforts to drop junior lightweight and junior welterweight classes to discourage matches between young opponents.[[CITE|46|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=%22National%20Boxing%20Association%20Head%20Flays%20Exploitati]] Operations ceased by the end of the 1933 season in the peak of the depression.[[CITE|47|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=Jessie%20A.%20Linthicum%20(25%20June%201933).%20%22RING%20AND%20RASS]][[CITE|48|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=Kevin%20Leonard%20(2%20October%202014).%20%22Laurel's%20outdoor%20]][[CITE|49|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=%22Hunt%20And%20Weiner%20Win%20Bouts%20In%20New%20Arena%20At%20Laurel%20]]

[[LINK|lang_en|Prohibition_in_the_United_States|Prohibition in the United States]] was repealed in 1934. Wasting little time, the Prince Georges Brewing Company planned a $500,000 brewery on 100 acres next to Laurel Park, but did not follow through.[[CITE|50|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=%22REALESTiTEDEALS%20AND%20BUILDING%20NEWS%20Plans%20For%20Const]]

In 1954, Johns Hopkins Applied Physics Laboratory built its campus west of Laurel in Howard County, using a Laurel address.[[CITE|51|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=%22Johns%20Hopkins%20Lets%20Contract%20in%20Md%22.%20*The%20Washingt]]

By 1960, Laurel anticipated massive growth from Fort Meade and NSA. The town still used the Patuxent River to drain sewage, and filed urban grants for water and sewage infrastructure. 5,000 houses were planned in the adjacent 1,200-acre [[LINK|lang_en|Maryland_City,_Maryland|Maryland City]] development. City Planner Harry Susini anticipated the National Capitol Planning Commission would use clustered development to prevent tightly massed population in Laurel by the year 2000.[[CITE|52|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=%22Laurel%20Prepares%20For%20Its%20New%20Era%3A%20Expected%20Growth%22]]

In the late 1960s, the county was at the peak of racial tensions. The situation peaked in Laurel in July 1967 when four men and a juvenile, affiliated with the [[LINK|lang_en|KKK|KKK]], attempted to burn St. Mark's United Methodist Church and then a private residence in the predominantly [[LINK|lang_en|African-American_neighborhood|African-American neighborhood]] of the Grove, prompting protests and police blockades. Due to cross-burning incidents, a Ku Klux Klan march, and several arsons and suspected arsons, temporary police barricades were erected throughout late July to prevent white residents from entering the Grove.[[CITE|53|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=%22Nightly%20Blockade%20of%20Negro%20Section%20In%20Laurel%20Is%20Or]][[CITE|54|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=Goeller%2C%20David%20(July%2016%2C%201967).%20%22Laurel's%20Negro%20Co]] In August 1967, it was announced that the city would re-purchase a privately owned swimming pool, which had been sold to a private club in 1949. The pool, which had only been available to white residents, was to be operated as an integrated public facility open to all.[[CITE|55|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=Pickett%2C%20Edward%20G%20(August%202%2C%201967).%20%22Laurel%20to%20Buy]]

On May 15, 1972, Governor [[LINK|lang_en|George_Wallace|George Wallace]] of [[LINK|lang_en|Alabama|Alabama]], running for the presidential nomination of the [[LINK|lang_en|United_States_Democratic_Party|Democratic Party]], was [[LINK|lang_en|Political_campaign|campaigning]] at a rally in the parking lot of [[LINK|lang_en|Laurel_Shopping_Center|Laurel Shopping Center]], near what is today a [[LINK|lang_en|Bank_of_America|Bank of America]] branch, when he was shot and [[LINK|lang_en|Paralysis|paralyzed]] by [[LINK|lang_en|Arthur_Bremer|Arthur Bremer]], a disturbed, out-of-work janitor (see *[[LINK|lang_en|An_Assassin%27s_Diary|An Assassin's Diary]]*).

On June 22, 1972, Laurel was impacted severely by [[LINK|lang_en|Hurricane_Agnes|Hurricane Agnes]], which caused the greatest [[LINK|lang_en|Flood|flooding]] ever recorded in Maryland.[[CITE|56|http://md.water.usgs.gov/publications/wsp-2375/md-dc/md-dc-html.html]] Several [[LINK|lang_en|Bridge|bridges]] were destroyed and the nearby T. Howard Duckett [[LINK|lang_en|Dam|Dam]] at [[LINK|lang_en|Rocky_Gorge_Reservoir|Rocky Gorge Reservoir]] was at capacity and posed a huge threat.[[CITE|57|http://www.mafsm.org/pdf/06_RegForm.pdf]] In 1975, the city council passed ordinances to create a historic district around Main Street.[[CITE|58|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=Sarah%20K.%20Krim%20(4%20September%201974).%20%22Historic%20Distri]]

In 1982, developer [[LINK|lang_en|Kingdon_Gould_III|Kingdon Gould III]] bought 3,539 acres of Laurel property (539 in [[LINK|lang_en|North_Laurel|North Laurel]]) in two deals for $15 million. The largest parcel lies between Laurel and Beltsville to be developed under the name [[LINK|lang_en|Konterra|Konterra]], buoyed by access to major highways via the construction of [[LINK|lang_en|Maryland_Route_200|Maryland Route 200]].[[CITE|59|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=%22Gould%20buys%203%2C539%20acres%20in%20two%20deals%22.%20*The%20Baltim]] [[CITE|full citation needed|undefined]]

The [[LINK|lang_en|Elizabeth_House|Elizabeth House]], a nonprofit food pantry and soup kitchen, was founded in 1988 to serve low-income residents of the Laurel area. This later grew to include emergency financial aid and transportation.[[CITE|60|https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/howard/laurel/ph-ll-elizabeth-house-renovations-20171012-story.html]]

A former 1840s mill workers' home on the northeast corner of 9th and Main Streets was renovated and opened as the [[LINK|lang_en|Laurel_Museum|Laurel Museum]] on May 1, 1996.  The museum features exhibits that highlight the history of Laurel and its citizens.  A gift shop is available, and museum admission is free.  The museum's [[LINK|lang_en|John_Calder_Brennan|John Calder Brennan]] Library is open to researchers by appointment.[[CITE|61|http://www.laurelhistory.org/pages/directions.html]]

items.text: 21st century

On September 24, 2001, a [[LINK|lang_en|Tornado|tornado]] passed [[LINK|lang_en|Maryland,_Virginia,_and_Washington,_D.C._tornado_outbreak_of_2001|through Laurel]] and left [[LINK|lang_en|Fujita_scale#Parameters|F3]] property damage, including significant roof damage to the [[LINK|lang_en|Laurel_High_School_(Laurel,_Maryland)|Laurel High School]] and the historic Harrison-Beard building.[[CITE|62|http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/local/bal-te.md.laurel26sep26,0,1440758.story?coll=bal-local-utility]]

Prior to the [[LINK|lang_en|September_11,_2001,_attacks|September 11, 2001, attacks]], all five of the [[LINK|lang_en|Aircraft_hijacking|hijackers]] of [[LINK|lang_en|American_Airlines_Flight_77|American Airlines Flight 77]] (which crashed into the Pentagon) stayed at various [[LINK|lang_en|Motel|motels]] in the Laurel area, including the Budget Host Valencia and Pin-Del motels in [[LINK|lang_en|Howard_County,_Maryland|Howard County]] just north of the city limits.[[CITE|63|/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number]] The wing of the Valencia where they stayed was demolished, and a new Sleep Inn was constructed on the ground, which opened in April 2007.  They accessed the [[LINK|lang_en|Internet|Internet]] through public computers at a [[LINK|lang_en|FedEx_Kinko%27s|Kinko's]] just south of the city limits. They also prepared for the hijacking by working out at a [[LINK|lang_en|Gold%27s_Gym|Gold's Gym]]; a report by [[LINK|lang_en|FBI|FBI]] Director [[LINK|lang_en|Robert_S._Mueller_III|Mueller]] states the gym was in Laurel,[[CITE|64|/wiki/Robert_S._Mueller_III]] while other sources list the location as [[LINK|lang_en|Greenbelt,_Maryland|Greenbelt, Maryland]],[[CITE|65|https://web.archive.org/web/20020405020924/http://www.newsday.com/ny-usflight232380680sep23.story]][[CITE|66|http://www.sptimes.com/News/092701/Worldandnation/The_trail_of_the_terr.shtml]] several miles to the south.

On August 29, 2005, Laurel adopted [[LINK|lang_en|Laurel,_Mississippi|Laurel, Mississippi]], as a [[LINK|lang_en|Sister_city|sister city]] to help with [[LINK|lang_en|Hurricane_Katrina|Hurricane Katrina]] relief and recovery.[[CITE|67|http://www.laurel.md.us/citizen_nov2006.htm]] In the two years following adoption, "the government, businesses and residents of Laurel, Md. ... raised more than $20,000 for Laurel, Miss."[[CITE|68|http://www.gazette.net/stories/090607/laurnew121344_32364.shtml]]

Geography

Laurel is located at . The city is situated on the bank of the [[LINK|lang_en|Patuxent_River|Patuxent River]], which was the power source for the [[LINK|lang_en|Cotton_mill|cotton mills]] that were the early industry of the town.

The [[LINK|lang_en|ZIP_Code|ZIP Codes]] for the incorporated city of Laurel are 20707, 20708, 20709, 20725, and 20756. Additionally, Although served by the Laurel post office, [[LINK|lang_en|Montpelier,_Maryland|Montpelier]] is not within the [[LINK|lang_en|City_limits|city limits]]; the same is true for the unincorporated communities of [[LINK|lang_en|Scaggsville,_Maryland|Scaggsville]] and [[LINK|lang_en|Whiskey_Bottom_Road|Whiskey Bottom]] in Howard County, and [[LINK|lang_en|Maryland_City,_Maryland|Maryland City]] and [[LINK|lang_en|Russett,_Maryland|Russett]] in Anne Arundel County.[[CITE|72|https://www.cityoflaurel.org/content/real-estate-property-taxes]] A small section of ZIP Code 20707 is located in [[LINK|lang_en|Montgomery_County,_Maryland|Montgomery County, Maryland]].[[CITE|73|https://planning.maryland.gov/msdc/Zipcode_map/2010/montzc10.pdf]][[CITE|74|https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1986/05/08/the-lost-colony-of-20707/0f6b22e2-233b-4bb2-97d1-d0aba5e76c15/]]

According to the [[LINK|lang_en|United_States_Census_Bureau|United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of 4.33 square miles (11.21Â km [[CITE||undefined]] ), of which, 4.30 square miles (11.14Â km [[CITE||undefined]] ) is land and 0.03 square miles (0.08Â km [[CITE||undefined]] ) is water.[[CITE|75|https://web.archive.org/web/20120125061959/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt]]
Climate

Typical of central Maryland, Laurel lies within the [[LINK|lang_en|Humid_subtropical_climate|Humid subtropical climate]] zone, with hot humid summers and cool to mild winters with high annual precipitation.  Laurel lies within USDA plant hardiness zones 7 and 8.[[CITE|76|http://www.arborday.org/treeinfo/ZoneInfo.cfm?ZipCode=20707&submit=Look+it+up%21]]

items.text: 2010 census

As of the [[LINK|lang_en|Census|census]][[CITE|4|http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml]] of 2010, there were 25,115 people, 10,498 households, and 5,695 families residing in the city. The [[LINK|lang_en|Population_density|population density]] was 5,840.7 inhabitants per square mile (2,255.1/km [[CITE||undefined]] ). There were 11,397 housing units at an average density of 2,650.5 per square mile (1,023.4/km [[CITE||undefined]] ). The racial makeup of the city was 30.1% [[LINK|lang_en|White_(U.S._Census)|White]], 48.9% [[LINK|lang_en|African_American_(U.S._Census)|African American]], 0.4% [[LINK|lang_en|Native_American_(U.S._Census)|Native American]], 9.2% [[LINK|lang_en|Asian_(U.S._Census)|Asian]], 0.1% [[LINK|lang_en|Race_(U.S._Census)|Pacific Islander]], 7.6% from [[LINK|lang_en|Race_(U.S._Census)|other races]], and 3.8% from two or more races. [[LINK|lang_en|Hispanic_(U.S._Census)|Hispanic]] or [[LINK|lang_en|Latino_(U.S._Census)|Latino]] of any race were 15.5% of the population.

There were 10,498 households of which 30.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 33.4% were [[LINK|lang_en|Marriage|married couples]] living together, 15.7% had a female householder with no husband present, 5.2% had a male householder with no wife present, and 45.8% were non-families. 37.6% of all households were made up of individuals and 6.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.37 and the average family size was 3.19.

The median age in the city was 33.7 years. 22.6% of residents were under the age of 18; 9.5% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 37.2% were from 25 to 44; 23.8% were from 45 to 64; and 7% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 47.7% male and 52.3% female.

Transportation

Laurel is traversed from north to south by [[LINK|lang_en|U.S._Route_1_in_Maryland|U.S. Route 1]] (US 1), which links [[LINK|lang_en|Key_West,_Florida|Key West, Florida]] with the [[LINK|lang_en|Canada%E2%80%93United_States_border|CanadaâUS border]] in [[LINK|lang_en|Maine|Maine]]. On the west, the city is bordered by [[LINK|lang_en|Interstate_95_in_Maryland|Interstate 95]], and beyond the eastern border lies the [[LINK|lang_en|Baltimore-Washington_Parkway|Baltimore-Washington Parkway]]. Crossing all of these highways is the east-west artery of [[LINK|lang_en|Maryland_Route_198|Maryland Route 198]] (MD 198), which intersects with US 1 in the heart of Laurel.

Other major state roads in Laurel are [[LINK|lang_en|Maryland_Route_216|MD 216]], which connects the city with southern Howard County, and [[LINK|lang_en|Maryland_Route_197|MD 197]], which runs from Laurel to [[LINK|lang_en|Bowie,_Maryland|Bowie]]. The eastern terminus of [[LINK|lang_en|Maryland_Route_200|MD 200]] (the Intercounty Connector) lies just south of the city limits and connects Laurel with [[LINK|lang_en|Gaithersburg,_Maryland|Gaithersburg]].

[[LINK|lang_en|Suburban_Airport|Suburban Airport]] was located on Brock Bridge Road, just over the Anne Arundel County border. For decades the airport provided [[LINK|lang_en|General_aviation|general aviation]] access for medivac helicopters, flight training, business travelers, and served as a relief airport for light traffic into and out of the two major regional airports. This airport closed in 2017.

Two [[LINK|lang_en|MARC_Train|MARC]] train stations on the [[LINK|lang_en|Camden_Line|Camden Line]] to Baltimore and Washington, D.C. are located in Laurel: [[LINK|lang_en|Laurel_(MARC_station)|Laurel Station]] and [[LINK|lang_en|Laurel_Race_Track_(MARC_station)|Laurel Racetrack Station]], the latter with minimal service. Laurel Station is a particularly notable example of the stations designed by [[LINK|lang_en|Ephraim_Francis_Baldwin|E. Francis Baldwin]] for the [[LINK|lang_en|Baltimore_and_Ohio_Railroad|Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]].

The [[LINK|lang_en|Washington_Metropolitan_Area_Transit_Authority|Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]] (WMATA) [[LINK|lang_en|Metrobus_(Washington,_D.C.)|Metrobus]] service provides four routes (87,[[CITE|80|https://www.wmata.com/schedules/timetables/upload/87-88.pdf]] 89, 89M,[[CITE|81|https://www.wmata.com/schedules/timetables/upload/89,89M_171217.pdf]] and Z7[[CITE|82|https://www.wmata.com/schedules/timetables/upload/Z7_170625.pdf]]) into Laurel, and local [[LINK|lang_en|Regional_Transportation_Agency_of_Central_Maryland|RTA]] bus service is available.  Several taxicab and shuttle services also support the region.
Emergency services

The [[LINK|lang_en|Laurel_Police_Department_(Maryland)|Laurel Police Department]] and the [[LINK|lang_en|Prince_George%27s_County_Police_Department|Prince George's County Police Department]] are the principal providers of the region's police officers. The [[LINK|lang_en|Maryland_State_Police|Maryland State Police]] patrol US 1, MD 198, and [[LINK|lang_en|Interstate_95_in_Maryland|Interstate 95]], which pass through the area, and the [[LINK|lang_en|United_States_Park_Police|United States Park Police]] patrol the [[LINK|lang_en|Baltimore-Washington_Parkway|Baltimore-Washington Parkway]] and its connectors.

PG County Police Department District 6 Station in [[LINK|lang_en|Beltsville,_Maryland|Beltsville CDP]] serves unincorporated areas near Laurel, and the City of Laurel itself is within the station's beat map.[[CITE|83|https://www.princegeorgescountymd.gov/Facilities/Facility/Details/District-6-Station-Beltsville-6]]

The primary emergency services providers for the City of Laurel and surrounding parts of Prince George's County are the Laurel Volunteer Fire Department (Company 10) and the Laurel Volunteer Rescue Squad (Company 49). Both companies are part of the Prince George's County Fire/EMS Department.

The Laurel Volunteer [[LINK|lang_en|Fire_Department|Fire Department]] was formed in 1902. Today the department is located at 7411 Cherry Lane. Volunteer staffing is supplemented by four career personnel from 7:00am to 3:00pm Monday through Friday excluding holidays. The company operates three fire engines (Engine 101, Engine 103, and Engine 104); and an aerial tower (Tower 10). [[LINK|lang_en|Ambulance|Ambulance]] service began December 11, 2006. A [[LINK|lang_en|Paramedic|paramedic]] unit staffed by two career personnel is also assigned to Company 10.

The Laurel Volunteer [[LINK|lang_en|Rescue_Squad|Rescue Squad]] was formed in 1952. Today the department is located at 14910 Bowie Road. Volunteer staffing is supplemented by four career personnel from 7:00am to 3:00pm Monday through Friday excluding holidays. The company operates one heavy rescue squad, one rescue-engine, three basic life support ambulances, and a [[LINK|lang_en|Swiftwater_rescue|swiftwater rescue]] team.

[[LINK|lang_en|Laurel_Regional_Hospital|Laurel Regional Hospital]], built in 1978 as the Greater Laurel-Beltsville Hospital, and now managed by Dimensions Healthcare System, is located on Van Dusen Road.
Government
Municipal government

Laurel is governed by a 5-member city council and a [[LINK|lang_en|Mayor|mayor]]. There are two political [[LINK|lang_en|Wards_of_the_United_States|wards]] in the city. The first ward is generally the area north of Maryland Route 198 and the second ward is to the south.[[CITE|84|http://www.laurel.md.us/voteward.htm]][[CITE|85|http://www.laurel.md.us/sites/default/files/votingwards.pdf]] Two council members are elected from each ward, and a council member is elected at large by residents of both wards.  City Council candidates must reside in Laurel a year before their election and during their full term of office.[[CITE|86|https://library.municode.com/md/laurel/codes/code_of_ordinances?nodeId=CH_ART300GO_S310CICO]]  Similarly, mayoral candidates must reside in the city for at least two years prior to their election.[[CITE|87|https://library.municode.com/md/laurel/codes/code_of_ordinances?nodeId=CH_ART300GO_S350MA]]

[[LINK|lang_en|Nonpartisan|Nonpartisan]] citywide elections are held every two years on the first Tuesday in November of the odd year.[[CITE|88|http://www.laurel.md.us/content/elections-and-voter-registration]]  Phelps Senior Center on the corner of Montgomery Street and 8th Street/St. Mary's Place[[CITE|89|http://www.laurel.md.us/cc.htm]] is the polling place for Ward 1, and the Robert J. DiPietro Community Center on Cypress Road is the polling place for Ward 2 voters.[[CITE|90|http://www.laurel.md.us/content/laurel-voting-wards]]  The next election, to select a mayor and city council members, will be held in November 2019 with elected individuals to take office at the second regular City Council meeting that follows.[[CITE|91|https://library.municode.com/md/laurel/codes/code_of_ordinances?nodeId=CH_ART600REEL_S602ELMACO]]  Regular meetings are held on the second and fourth Mondays of each month.[[CITE|92|https://www.cityoflaurel.org/clerk/meetings/about-mayor%C2%A0and-city-council-meetings-and-work-sessions]]

The council elects one of its members to serve as [[LINK|lang_en|President_(government_title)#Sub-national|president]]. The president of the city council presides over council meetings and can act in a limited capacity as mayor if the mayor is unavailable. Council members serve for two years each [[LINK|lang_en|Term_of_office|term]]; the mayor serves for four years.

Media and culture
Media

[[LINK|lang_en|Television|Television]] arrived in Laurel with the establishment of the first TV broadcast stations in Washington in 1946. For decades, Laurel has been served by the VHF TV channels 4 ([[LINK|lang_en|WRC-TV|WRC-TV]] / [[LINK|lang_en|NBC|NBC]]), 5 ([[LINK|lang_en|WTTG|WTTG]] / [[LINK|lang_en|Fox_Broadcasting_Company|FOX]]), 7 ([[LINK|lang_en|WJLA-TV|WJLA-TV]] / [[LINK|lang_en|American_Broadcasting_Company|ABC]]), and 9 ([[LINK|lang_en|WUSA_(TV)|WUSA]] / [[LINK|lang_en|CBS|CBS]]) from Washington; channels 2 ([[LINK|lang_en|WMAR-TV|WMAR-TV]] / [[LINK|lang_en|American_Broadcasting_Company|ABC]]), 11 ([[LINK|lang_en|WBAL-TV|WBAL-TV]] / [[LINK|lang_en|NBC|NBC]]), and 13 ([[LINK|lang_en|WJZ-TV|WJZ-TV]] / [[LINK|lang_en|CBS|CBS]]) from Baltimore; plus [[LINK|lang_en|Maryland_Public_Television|Maryland Public Television]] from Annapolis and Baltimore. In addition, there are dozens of [[LINK|lang_en|UHF|UHF]] TV stations from Washington, Baltimore, and [[LINK|lang_en|Annapolis,_Maryland|Annapolis]]. From these three cities, scores of AM and [[LINK|lang_en|FM_broadcasting|FM]] [[LINK|lang_en|Radio|radio]] stations reach Laurel.

Laurel has one local newspaper, the *[[LINK|lang_en|Laurel_Leader|Laurel Leader]]*, and one [[LINK|lang_en|Mediumwave|mediumwave]] [[LINK|lang_en|AM_broadcasting|AM radio]] station, [[LINK|lang_en|WCLM_(AM)|WCLM]] 900, with an [[LINK|lang_en|Adult_contemporary_music|adult contemporary]] format.

With its location between Washington and Baltimore, Laurel is also served by their daily newspapers *[[LINK|lang_en|The_Washington_Post|The Washington Post]]*, *[[LINK|lang_en|The_Washington_Times|The Washington Times]]* and  *[[LINK|lang_en|The_Baltimore_Sun|The Baltimore Sun]]*. Many Laurel residents also read a free [[LINK|lang_en|Newspaper|newspaper]], the *[[LINK|lang_en|Washington_Examiner|Washington Examiner]]*.
Arts

Local [[LINK|lang_en|Performing_arts|performing arts]] outlets include the [[LINK|lang_en|Venus_Theatre|Venus Theatre]],  [[LINK|lang_en|/www.laurelmillplayhouse.org|Laurel Mill Playhouse]], [[LINK|lang_en|Central_Maryland_Chorale|Central Maryland Chorale]] (formerly Laurel Oratorio Society) and [[LINK|lang_en|/arts.pgparks.com/Our_Facilities/Montpelier_Arts_Center/About_Montpelier.htm|Montpelier Arts Center]], which also features an [[LINK|lang_en|Art_gallery|art gallery]].  Another local exhibitor is the [[LINK|lang_en|//web.archive.org/web/20070929015231/http://www.wssc.dst.md.us/info/gallery/|WSSC Art Gallery]].
Events

The city government supports an annual LakeFest in May and [[LINK|lang_en|Independence_Day_(United_States)|Independence Day]] celebration each July.  Since 1981, the Laurel [[LINK|lang_en|Chamber_of_commerce|Board of Trade]] has sponsored a Main Street Festival (held on Saturday of [[LINK|lang_en|Mother%27s_Day_(United_States)|Mother's Day]] weekend) each May, and since 1995 a RiverFest each October.  The Montpelier Mansion grounds have hosted an annual festival the first weekend in May since 1971, updated in 2007 to focus on an "herb, tea and arts" theme.[[CITE|97|https://openlibrary.org/search?q=Garnes%2C%20Kathy.%20%22Montpelier%20herb%2C%20tea%20and%20art%20fest%20]]

items.text: Education
Primary and secondary schools
Public schools within and serving the city limits

[[LINK|lang_en|Prince_George%27s_County_Public_Schools|Prince George's County Public Schools]] serves residents within Laurel's city limits.[[CITE|106|https://www.cityoflaurel.org/system/files/files/cityoflaurelzoningmap2017.pdf]]

Many city residents are zoned to Laurel Elementary School or Scotchtown Hills Elementary School, both within the city limits. There are also residential portions of the city zoned to schools outside the city limits: Bond Mill Elementary School in [[LINK|lang_en|West_Laurel,_Maryland|West Laurel CDP]], Deerfield Run Elementary School in [[LINK|lang_en|South_Laurel,_Maryland|South Laurel CDP]], Oaklands Elementary School in South Laurel, and Vansville Elementary School in an [[LINK|lang_en|Unincorporated_area|unincorporated area]] near [[LINK|lang_en|Beltsville,_Maryland|Beltsville]].[[CITE|107|http://gis.pgcps.org/mapgallery/Maps/Boundaries%20-%20Elementary.pdf]] Two public middle schools, Dwight D. Eisenhower Middle School in South Laurel CDP and Martin Luther King Jr. Middle School in Beltsville CDP serve the actual city of Laurel.[[CITE|108|http://gis.pgcps.org/mapgallery/Maps/Boundaries%20-%20Middle.pdf]] [[LINK|lang_en|Laurel_High_School_(Maryland)|Laurel High School]] in the city limits serves the city of Laurel.[[CITE|109|http://gis.pgcps.org/mapgallery/Maps/Boundaries%20-%20High.pdf]]

During the era of legally-required racial [[LINK|lang_en|School_segregation_in_the_United_States|segregation of schools]], black students from Laurel attended [[LINK|lang_en|Lakeland_High_School_(Maryland)|Lakeland High School]] in [[LINK|lang_en|College_Park,_Maryland|College Park]] in the period 1928â1950,[[CITE|110|https://issuu.com/mncppc/docs/aapgc]][[CITE|111|/wiki/Arcadia_Publishing]] and [[LINK|lang_en|Fairmont_Heights_High_School|Fairmont Heights High School]], then near [[LINK|lang_en|Fairmount_Heights,_Maryland|Fairmount Heights]], from 1950 to 1964; around 1964, legally-required racial segregation of schools ended.[[CITE|112|https://web.archive.org/web/20051004001621/http://www.pgcps.org:80/~fmhts/history.html]]
Public schools nearby

Nearby elementary schools serving areas outside of the Laurel city limits include Bond Mill, Deerfield Run, James H. Harrison, Montpelier, Oaklands, and Scotchtown Hills Elementary Schools in Prince George's County; Brock Bridge and Maryland City Elementary Schools in Anne Arundel County; Burtonsville Elementary School in Montgomery County, and Forest Ridge, Gorman Crossing, [[LINK|lang_en|Hammond_Elementary_School|Hammond]], and [[LINK|lang_en|Laurel_Woods_Elementary_School|Laurel Woods Elementary]] Schools in Howard County.

Areas near Laurel in adjacent counties are served by MacArthur and Meade Middle Schools in Anne Arundel County, Benjamin Banneker Middle School in Montgomery County, and Hammond and Murray Hill Middle Schools in Howard County.

Other public high schools which serve the adjacent areas outside Prince George's County include [[LINK|lang_en|Meade_Senior_High_School|Meade High School]] in Anne Arundel County, [[LINK|lang_en|Paint_Branch_High_School|Paint Branch High School]] in Montgomery County, and [[LINK|lang_en|Atholton_High_School|Atholton]], [[LINK|lang_en|Hammond_High_School_(Columbia,_Maryland)|Hammond]] and [[LINK|lang_en|Reservoir_High_School|Reservoir High Schools]] in Howard County. A notable [[LINK|lang_en|Magnet_school|magnet school]] in Prince George's County is [[LINK|lang_en|Eleanor_Roosevelt_High_School_(Greenbelt,_MD)|Eleanor Roosevelt High School]].
District of Columbia alternative school

[[LINK|lang_en|District_of_Columbia_Public_Schools|District of Columbia Public Schools]] operates an alternative middle and high school near Laurel named [[LINK|lang_en|Maya_Angelou_Academy|Maya Angelou Academy]].

items.text: Colleges, universities, and trade schools

[[LINK|lang_en|Prince_George%27s_Community_College|Prince George's Community College]] and [[LINK|lang_en|Howard_Community_College|Howard Community College]] share a campus in Laurel called the Laurel College Center.[[CITE|114|http://www.laurelcollegecenter.org/]]
[[LINK|lang_en|Capitol_Technology_University|Capitol Technology University]] is located south of Laurel.
The Anne Arundel County section of Laurel hosts the Woodland [[LINK|lang_en|Job_Corps|Job Corps]] Center.
Public libraries

[[LINK|lang_en|Prince_George%27s_County_Memorial_Library_System|Prince George's County Memorial Library System]] operates the [[LINK|lang_en|Laurel_Branch_Library|Laurel Branch Library]] at the intersection of Seventh Street and Talbott Avenue.[[CITE|115|https://www.pgcmls.info/website/branch/location/Laurel]]  The "Maryland City at Russett" branch of the Anne Arundel County Public Library is also available to Laurel area residents.
Sports and recreation

Laurel's Department of Parks & Recreation sponsors seasonal sports leagues for adults, with youth leagues in the area offered by Laurel Little League, Greater Laurel United Soccer Club (GLUSC), Laurel Soccer Club (LSC),[[CITE|116|http://www.laurelsoccerclub.org/]] and the Laurel [[LINK|lang_en|Boys_%26_Girls_Clubs_of_America|Boys and Girls Club]].[[CITE|117|http://laurel.md.us/sportsprog.htm]]  Events are held among eleven city parks, three athletic fields, and three [[LINK|lang_en|Community_center|community centers]]. The city also operates a municipal [[LINK|lang_en|Swimming_pool|swimming pool]] and [[LINK|lang_en|Tennis_court|tennis courts]].[[CITE|118|http://laurel.md.us/prfac.htm]] Four indoor facilities and seven outdoor facilities are available for private rental.[[CITE|119|http://laurel.md.us/prfees.htm]]

The Fairland Sports and Athletic Complex on the grounds of the Fairland Regional Park, southwest of the city limits, is operated by the [[LINK|lang_en|Maryland-National_Capital_Park_and_Planning_Commission|Maryland-National Capital Park and Planning Commission]].  These facilities offer a broad variety of activities including swimming, [[LINK|lang_en|Gymnastics|gymnastics]], tennis, [[LINK|lang_en|Racquetball|racquetball]], [[LINK|lang_en|Weight_training|weight training]], child sitting, and [[LINK|lang_en|Massage|massage]] therapy.[[CITE|120|http://www.pgparks.com/places/sportsfac/specialized.html]]

Also located within Fairland Regional Park, [[LINK|lang_en|The_Gardens_Ice_House|The Gardens Ice House]] skating facility offers three [[LINK|lang_en|Ice_rink|rinks]] for [[LINK|lang_en|Ice_skating|ice skating]] lessons, public skating, [[LINK|lang_en|Figure_skating|figure skating]], [[LINK|lang_en|Hockey|hockey]], [[LINK|lang_en|Speed_skating|speed skating]], and [[LINK|lang_en|Curling|curling]].  Recent additional activities include [[LINK|lang_en|Basketball|basketball]] and [[LINK|lang_en|Lacrosse|lacrosse]].[[CITE|121|http://www.thegardensicehouse.com/]] The Gardens Ice House is also home to the [[LINK|lang_en|Washington_Jr._Nationals|Washington Jr. Nationals]] [[LINK|lang_en|Junior_ice_hockey|Tier III Junior A]] [[LINK|lang_en|Ice_hockey|ice hockey]] team, playing in the [[LINK|lang_en|Atlantic_Junior_Hockey_League|Atlantic Junior Hockey League]], as well as the [[LINK|lang_en|Maryland_Reapers|Maryland Reapers]], an indoor football franchise of the [[LINK|lang_en|American_Indoor_Football|American Indoor Football]] League.

The Laurel Roller Skating Center, just north of the city limits, provides a location for public [[LINK|lang_en|Roller_skating|roller skating]],[[CITE|122|http://washingtontimes.com/weekend/20040224-102240-4100r.htm]] and [[LINK|lang_en|Bowlero_Corporation|AMF Bowling]] has a location in Laurel.
